dismissalText.commentary: Joe Root run out (Wiese/†de Kock) 125 (113b 10x4 5x6 165m) SR: 110.61

dismissalComment.html: oh no, Root and Stokes are standing together mid-pitch... This has not gone to plan. Root spanked a drive into the stumps at the non-striker's end, set off, stuttered, called again as the ball ricocheted to short midwicket - Stokes then started and stopped as Wiese hared after it and de Kock has a simple job to complete the run-out

dismissalText.commentary: Jason Roy run out (Morkel/†de Kock) 20 (23b 4x4 0x6 23m) SR: 86.95

dismissalComment.html: slashed over gully, in the air but it bounces wide of third man, Roy wants a second... Morkel gets the return in hard and flat over the stumps, de Kock breaks the bails smartly and then throws for the non-striker's end as well, seemingly doubting whether he had managed to beat Roy. But a quick check upstairs confirms Roy's bat was millimetresshort! He's run himself out!

commentTextItems.html: on the pads, nudged away, South Africa have rampaged to an outstanding seven-wicket win!

commentPostTextItems.html: 9.15pm So, that wraps that up. A wonderful win for South Africa, Centurion has been their fortress on this tour so far. Thanks for all your comments, have a read of George Dobell's match report, and the plays of the day, before you go. From Alan Gardner and myself, goodnight.
9.07pm Right, time for some presentations ... Eoin Morgan speaks: "Joe Root was outstanding, Alex Hales played a knock around him and going into the half-way stage I thought we were in the game."

"It's as simple as working on the basics, they had an incredible opening partnership but we didn't hit the right length. The biggest challenge for bowlers is taking wickets which creates a positive mindset.
"South Africa have come back strong but hopefully we can bounce back quickly."

AB de Villiers collects his winners' cheque. "We needed that win, the boys were up for it. A bit of urgency in the field, a bit of hunger, and we had that today, even though we haven't had the greatest series up to date.
"A little bit of local knowledge, we felt it was definitely a chasing wicket. I was going to bowl first, it's difficult to chase at night."
"Fantastic knock by both of them," he says of Amla and de Kock. "Slowly but surely we are getting back into the series."

Unsurprisingly, the Man of the Match is Quinton de Kock for his outstanding 135. "It was a matter of getting in and batting normally. Centurion does get slow but at night with a bit of dew it comes on better."

8.58pm So, what a performance from South Africa. Two outstanding hundreds from Quinton de Kock and Hashim Amla, and South Africa are suddenly back in the series. They still trail 2-1, but what a lift that chase will give the squad as they head to the Wanderers, one of their favourite one-day haunts. England thought that their total of 318 for 8 should have been ample, but it just goes to show how little wriggle-room there is in modern ODI cricket. Too many errors in that innings - two run-outs, a misfiring Morgan and a first-baller for Jos Buttler - and Joe Root's brilliant 125 wasn't sufficient to keep them in the hunt.

commentTextItems.html: free hit and help yourself! Smashed gratuitously over the bowler's head!
England are just prendring le Michel now. A vile wide full toss, a toe-ende thump into the covers, and very nearly a catch - expect of course it is a no-ball and a free hit ...

commentPostTextItems.html: Saad: "Unfortunately for Jordan, he now has a series bowling average....and it's 143" How cruel

commentPreTextItems.html: So, a bit of AB love for his Centurion home crowd after all

commentTextItems.html: wide outside off, a miscued drill and Jordan gathers

commentPostTextItems.html: Arjuna: "Well looks like Jordan was bowling to a plan. Frustrate batsmen by bowling wides down leg side and bowl one outside off stump. IT worked. Common guys he is not that bad." Baldrick couldn't have plotted it better

commentPostTextItems.html: vikki: "Hey Allan/Andrew, I forecasted that SA will win thins match by 8 wickets!!! didn't I??? " You certainly did! You were also wrong!

commentTextItems.html: round the wicket, way down the leg side, that is just a bit rubbish really
short again, helped round the corner, easy peasy

commentPostTextItems.html: Mulkey: "Never mind DLS & DRS, I think Jordan should be looking at the DSS!" Zing!

commentTextItems.html: too full, on the pads, tickled fine, I think Jordan fancies an early bath
short, thumped round the corner. Jordan's round-the-wicket ploy is working about as well as Centurion's electricity supply
banged in short, that's Jordan's one for the over. Odd and anachronistic rule that that is ...
wristy and sumptuous, clean through the covers! That's just delightful

headshotImage.caption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: pushed to mid-on from a full length

commentPostTextItems.html: Happy: "Happy is happy that SA is trying to finish this quickly, am at Sandton and it is raining heavily here..." I think DLS would be forgiving if they couldn't get to the end now ...

Bharat Dhir: "How long can one player be in the side just for his fielding? I guess we will know the answer when England decide to drop Jordan." fair point. There's always the option of taking a sniper's rifle to Reece Topley's hamstrings at the end of his spell and sending Jordan out as a sub fielder ...

commentTextItems.html: wristy flick in front of square on the leg side, Amla so easily into position
full face of the bat, pumped down the ground. England can't lay a glove on South Africa at the moment

commentPostTextItems.html: Shantanu: "splendiferousness isn't a word my dear Miller. truthiness is though. So chew toothily on that but of truthiness." Cobblers. You'll be telling me that supercalifragilisticexpialidocious doesn't exist next ...

headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: shorter and sharper, that was livelier! Du Plessis gets the hurry-up ...
down the leg side, Jordan is adamant there was something on that, but it was a low full toss as well, so he didn't really deserve anything better

dismissalText.commentary: Chris Jordan c Duminy b Abbott 3 (5b 0x4 0x6 8m) SR: 60

dismissalComment.html: two in two, Jordan sends it down the throat of deep extra cover! Canny slower ball from Abbott, anticipating the big shot and Jordan lemming-ed it straight to the man on the fence. England could get bowled out here

headshotImage.caption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Quinton de Kock c Root b Rashid 135 (117b 16x4 4x6 147m) SR: 115.38

dismissalComment.html: this one does carry, however, a tired welly to cover, and a wonderful innings comes to an end!

dismissalText.commentary: Hashim Amla c †Buttler b Jordan 127 (130b 13x4 2x6 187m) SR: 97.69

dismissalComment.html: outside off, and snicked through to the keeper! Jordan finally finds a line that doesn't get walloped or wided, and that's the end of a sensational match-winning innings
